Module 4 - Multiple Linear Regression

In-Class Analysis

Data and Description

Note: The majority of the code needed below can be found in the example files from lecture, replacing the variable names with those you create for this data set. You may also want to draw on your code from the in-class coding exercise from Module 2 for diagnostics.

Companies are continually evaluating supervisors to, not only determine adequate performance, but also gauge employee morale (an important indicator for employee productivity). In an effort to understand the important aspects of a good supervisor, employees at a certain company were asked to provide an overall rating and scores on 6 characteristics of their immediate managers (30 in total). Employees were asked to rate the following statements on a scale from 0 to 100 (0 meaning completely disagree to 100 meaning completely agree):

Variable Description
Rating Overall rating of supervisor performance. Higher score means better supervisor.
complaints Score for Your supervisor handles employee complaints appropriately.
Privileges Score for Your supervisor allows special privileges.
Learn Score for Your supervisor provides opportunities to learn new things.
Raises Score for Your supervisor bases raises on performance.
Critical Score for Your supervisor is too critical of poor performance.
Advance Score for I am not satisfied with the rate I am advancing in the company.

Do the following:

  1. Download the Supervisor.txt file from Canvas and put it in the same folder as this R Markdown file.
  2. Read in the data set, call it super, and take a look at the top few rows.

3. The errors are independent.

You do not need to do anything for this assumption, as it is typically assessed by considering the way in which the data were sampled. However, this assumption should always be considered in linear regression.

4. The errors are normally distributed and centered at zero

The assumptions seem to be roughly met, although it may be worthwhile to consider transformations, likely of the response variable since there are potentially issues with equal variance/normality. Another possibility would be to consider interactions between predictors, which we will discuss in future modules. For now, we will proceed to do inference with this model.

Confidence Intervals/Bands

Obtain confidence intervals for the slope coefficients in the model using `confint. Convert these into simultaneous confidence intervals using either the Bonferonni or Scheffe method. Review (perhaps with someone sitting near you) the difference between the ordinary and simultaneous intervals.

p <- ncol(super) - 1 # number of predictors
confint(super.lm, parm = 2:(p + 1))
##                  2.5 %    97.5 %
## Complaints  0.28016866 0.9462066
## Privileges -0.35381806 0.2077178
## Learn      -0.02827872 0.6689430
## Raises     -0.37642935 0.5398936
## Critical   -0.26570179 0.3424647
## Advance    -0.58571106 0.1515977
## <NA>                NA        NA
## <NA>                NA        NA
tbon <- qt(1 - 0.05/(2*p), nrow(super) - p - 1)
schef <- sqrt(6*qf(1 - 0.05, p + 1, nrow(super) - p - 1))
mult <- min(tbon, schef) # take smaller of the two

SimCIbetas <- cbind(super.lm$coefficients[-1] - mult*summary(super.lm)$coefficients[-1, 2],
                    super.lm$coefficients[-1] + mult*summary(super.lm)$coefficients[-1, 2])
SimCIbetas
##                  [,1]      [,2]
## Complaints  0.1240813 1.1022939
## Privileges -0.4854151 0.3393149
## Learn      -0.1916741 0.8323383
## Raises     -0.5911715 0.7546358
## Critical   -0.4082269 0.4849898
## Advance    -0.7585009 0.3243875

The intervals provided by `confint are to be interpreted separately; for each one, we can say that it contains the true slope coefficient for the predictor with 95% confidence. For the simultaneous intervals, we can say with 95% confidence that all of the intervals contain their true parameter value.

Create an effects plot for the `Complaints predictor, setting all other predictors to their median value. Add a 90% simultaneous confidence band to this plot, and review (again, perhaps with a neighbor) the meaning of this band.

comp.grid <- with(super, seq(min(Complaints), max(Complaints), length.out = 50))
comp.df <- with(super, data.frame(Complaints = comp.grid,
                                  Privileges = rep(median(Privileges), length(comp.grid)),
                                  Learn = rep(median(Learn), length(comp.grid)),
                                  Raises = rep(median(Raises), length(comp.grid)),
                                  Critical = rep(median(Critical), length(comp.grid)),
                                  Advance = rep(median(Advance), length(comp.grid))))
CBvals <- predict(super.lm, newdata = comp.df, se.fit = TRUE)

sim.mult <- sqrt((p + 1)*qf(0.9, p + 1, nrow(super) - p - 1))
comp.df$fit <- CBvals$fit
comp.df$SCBlow <- CBvals$fit - sim.mult*CBvals$se.fit
comp.df$SCBhi <- CBvals$fit + sim.mult*CBvals$se.fit

ComplaintsEffectPlot <- ggplot(data = comp.df) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Complaints, y = fit), color = 'black') +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Complaints, y = SCBlow), color = 'blue', size = 0.7) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Complaints, y = SCBhi), color = 'blue', size = 0.7) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = SCBlow, ymax = SCBhi, x = Complaints), fill = 'blue', alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Effect Plot for Complaints with Simultaneous Confidence Band",
       x = "Complaints", y = "Rating")
ComplaintsEffectPlot

The black line represents the estimated mean response as the Complaints score changes, with all other scores set to their median value, giving the models estimate of the average supervisor ratings for different predictor values. For each value of Complaints, the confidence band at that value marks the confidence interval for the mean response. By creating simultaneous confidence bands, we are 95% certain that all of these pointwise confidence intervals simultaneously contain the true average rating.

Hypothesis testing

Examine the summary output of your multiple linear regression model. Carefully interpret the following values:

(a) The p-value of 0.000903 for the `Complaints predictor

Once the effects of the other scores (Privileges, Learn, Raises, Critical, and Advance) have been controlled for, the Complaints score still has a highly significant effect on the average rating of a supervisor.

(b) The p-value of 0.71548 for the `Raises predictor

Although higher ratings are associated with higher Raises scores, once the other scores are controlled for, Raises no longer has an effect on average ratings.

(c) The p-value of 1.24e-05 for the global F-test (last line of the output)

At least one of the predictors has a significant linear effect on average supervisor ratings.

(d) The Multiple R-squared value of 0.7326

73.26% of the variability in this sample of supervisor ratings can be explained by a linear relationship with the surveyed scores.

Verify (using a partial F-test) that, once the effect of `Complaints is included, all of the other predictors have estimated effects that are not statistically significantly different from zero. Explain (perhaps just verbally to a classmate) why it would be incorrect to draw this conclusion just because none of the individual effect p-values in the summary output are below 0.05.

super.lm0 <- lm(Rating ~ Complaints, data = super)
anova(super.lm0, super.lm)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: Rating ~ Complaints
## Model 2: Rating ~ Complaints + Privileges + Learn + Raises + Critical + 
##     Advance
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1     28 1369.4                           
## 2     23 1149.0  5    220.38 0.8823 0.5086

The statement is that, after only controlling for `Complaints, none of the others are significant. In other words, we want to compare the model with only the Complaints score to the model involving all scores. However, the individual effect p-values do not test this. For example, the p-value for Learn is comparing the model with all score except Learn (the reduced model) to the model with all scores.

Summary and Conclusions

Although several of the scores seem to be associated with a supervisors overall rating, the moderate to high correlations between scores indicate that not all of the scores are equally important in the regression model. This is confirmed by the added variable plots as well as statistical insignificance of many of the effects, which we have some confidence in after assessing the model assumptions using our diagnostic tools. Overall, it appears that `Complaints is the key variable that influences a supervisors average rating, with higher scores (indicative of better perception of the supervisors handling of complaints) leading to higher average ratings.
